observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team a written justification on the direct credits to PPE accounts totaling ₱13,415,319.39 to provide for depreciation expenses per JEV No. 100-2024-12-A1205, otherwise, prepare a JEV to correct the error, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team a written justification, including supporting computation and documentation, on the journal entry made in JEV No. 100-2024-12-A1202, otherwise, prepare a JEV to correct the error;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare a JEV to correct the error in the recording of payment for the construction/rehabilitation/ improvement of the local Public Market costing ₱1,475,102.92 to its proper PPE account, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to compute and prepare a JEV to provide for the allowance for depreciation of the local Public Market in accordance with relevant provisions on depreciation;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team the revised financial statements taking into consideration the proposed adjusting journal entries, the noted differences between the Statement of Financial Position and the Notes to the Financial Statements, and the misstatements in Notes 8 and 17 as presented in Appendices E, F, G, H, and I;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team the CY 2024 general ledgers for all PPE accounts and ensure that all CY 2024 amounts in Note 8 are based on the CY 2024 general ledger balances and transaction totals;
instruct the members of the Inventory Committee conduct reconciliation on the discrepancies noted between the Statement of Financial Position and the RPCPPE totaling ₱319,148,046.95 and adjust any of the records as necessary to come up with the reconciled balance of all PPE accounts. Ensure that the RPCPPE is prepared in the format as prescribed in Annex 49 of the Manual;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that PPE additions are properly recorded in the General Journal upon delivery or completion in compliance with Section 122 of the Manual;
prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards per type of property and complete with the necessary information as provided by each template. Ensure that all Property Numbers are unique for every type of property or asset, and that all PPE additions are easily identifiable to either a new or an existing PPE item; and
initiate steps towards the carrying out of the one-time cleansing of PPE in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the Management through the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
determine the accumulated depreciation and carrying amount of the semi-expendable properties with cost totaling ₱7,686,360.05 as presented in Appendix E and whether or not these properties are already issued to end-users as of December 31, 2024;
prepare JEVs to reclassify the semi-expendable properties totaling ₱7,686,360.05 in the books following the illustrative accounting entries as presented in Annex C of COA Circular No. 2024-004 and submit to the Audit Team the revised CY 2024 financial statements for further evaluation;
assign focal persons and/or provide for additional manpower in the Accounting Office for the purpose of retrieving source documents and identifying and detecting other items booked under PPE or Inventories that qualify as semi-expendable properties, with the end in view of reclassifying these items as semi-expendable properties in the CY 2025 financial statements; and
ensure that all semi-expendable properties acquired prior to the effectivity of COA Circular No. 2024-006 be issued and/or maintained with SPCs, SPLCs, and ICSs, as applicable, in compliance with Items 3.6 to 3.8 of the said Circular.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
revise the CY 2024 Notes to the Financial Statements to properly present the required disclosure on local roads in the format as prescribed in Annex B of the Circular;
conduct a complete physical count of all road networks under their jurisdiction and render the Report on the Physical Count of LRN in the format as prescribed in Annex C of the Circular;
expedite the preparation and/or maintenance of the Report on LRN and LRN Property Cards for each local road in the formats as prescribed in Annex A and E of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied; and
expedite the preparation and maintenance of the Local Road Network Ledger Cards for each local road in the format as prescribed in Annex D of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied.
During the exit conference, Management explained that the physical count was only done for recent road projects, hence, the deficiencies noted.

We recommended and Management agreed to submit to the Audit Team a written justification, including other necessary documents and reports, for further evaluation thereof.
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor and all employees/officials concerned agreed to implement inventory management controls as required in the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, taking into consideration the following:
supplies and materials are properly recorded as inventories in the General Journal upon delivery in compliance with Section 122 of the Manual;
Stock Cards for each inventory following the format as prescribed in Annex 36 of the Manual are prepared and updated;
Supplies Ledger Cards for each type of inventory following the format as prescribed in Annex 7 of the Manual are prepared and updated;
supplies and materials expenses are recorded in the General Journals, duly supported with the weekly SSMI and accompanied with RISs pursuant to Section 121 of the Manual;
physical counts of inventories are conducted in the first and second semesters, and that the duly approved RPCI be prepared and submitted to the Audit Team in the deadlines set in the Manual; and
results of physical count of inventories be reconciled against the Stock Cards and the Stock Ledger Cards with the end in view of identifying any shortages and unaccounted inventory items, exhaustion of remedies for any lost or damaged inventories, and taking appropriate adjustments in the appropriate property records and accounting books.

We recommended and Management agreed to initiate steps towards the revision of the Plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality, with emphasis on the following:
filling-in of vacancies in the Plantilla, especially the Level 2 positions;
hiring JO personnel only for the purpose of implementing local projects in accordance with Section 77 of RA No. 7160;
creation of the required divisions in the MTO, such Cash Division, Revenue Division, Administrative Section, IT Unit, and Supplies and Property Division/Unit;
creation and filling-in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the Municipal Assessor’s Office in compliance with RA No. 7160 and the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations; and
creation and filling-in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the MDRRMO in compliance with RA No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1.

We recommended and Management through the concerned official agreed to:
submit a written explanation on the noted deficiencies, including the non-implementation of seven GAD PPAs with a total budget of ₱1,807,800.00 for further evaluation;
prepare and submit to the Audit Team for further evaluation a revised CY 2024 GAD Accomplishment Report duly signed by the Chairperson of the GFPS. Ensure that Actual Results column fully describes the necessary description as required in Annex E of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended;
ensure that the CY 2024 GAD AR is duly received by the Provincial Planning and Development Office and to the DILG in compliance with Item 4.1.C.5 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended; and
ensure that the CY 2024 GAD AR is submitted to the DILG for posting in the Full Disclosure Policy Portal in compliance with DILG MC No. 2019-149.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to require the personnel concerned to immediately render full liquidation of their respective overdue cash advances, otherwise implement the applicable remedy such as withholding of salaries and other amounts due from them or initiate the filing of appropriate administrative and criminal proceedings against the accountable officers who failed to settle their accountabilities after the demand;
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to the same officials or employees who have yet to liquidate their previous cash advances pursuant to Sec. 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Monitor liquidation of CAs granted to ensure that there are no delays in the accounting and recording thereof; and
Require the accountable officers to submit the liquidation documents timely pursuant to the prescribed due date.
